               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18290409-322-off1814-c2243" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-defend2980 t18290409-322-off1814 t18290409-322-verdict1822"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18290409-322-off1817-c2245" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-defend2984 t18290409-322-off1817 t18290409-322-verdict1824"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18290409-322-off1817-c2292" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-defend3032 t18290409-322-off1817 t18290409-322-verdict1824"></join>
         
               <p>Fifth Middlesex Jury.</p>
               <p>999. 
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-defend2978" type="defendantName">
                     THOMAS GEORGE 
                     HAWKINS
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2978" type="surname" value="HAWKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2978" type="given" value="THOMAS GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2978" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2978" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             and 
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-defend2980" type="defendantName">
                     JOHN 
                     BALLARD
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2980" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2980" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2980" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2980" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             were indicted for <rs id="t18290409-322-off1814" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-off1814" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-off1814" type="offenceSubcategory" value="housebreaking"></interp>
               feloniously breaking and entering the dwelling-house of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18290409-322-victim2982" type="victimName">
                           John Smith 
                           Carr
                        <interp inst="t18290409-322-victim2982" type="surname" value="Carr"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-322-victim2982" type="given" value="John Smith"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-322-victim2982" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , on the <rs id="t18290409-322-cd1815" type="crimeDate">17th of March</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-off1814 t18290409-322-cd1815"></join>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-off1817 t18290409-322-cd1815"></join>, at St. Andrews, Holborn, and stealing therein 1 chest, value 7s.; 1 tin-box, value 2s.; 50 sovereigns, 10 crowns, 6 half-crowns, 30 shillings, 4 sixpences, and three 20l. Bank-notes, his property
            </rs>, against the Statute; and 
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="defendantName">
                     GEORGE 
                     BALLARD
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="age" value="52"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend2984" type="age" value="40"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             and ANN (HIS <rs id="t18290409-322-deflabel1816" type="occupation">WIFE</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-defend3032 t18290409-322-deflabel1816"></join>) were indicted for <rs id="t18290409-322-off1817" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-off1817" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-off1817" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>
               feloniously receiving, on the same day, at the same parish, 22 sovereigns, part and parcel of the said monies, they well knowing them to have been stolen
            </rs>; against the Statute.</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>MR. 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2985">
                  JOHN 
                  SMITH CARR
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2985" type="surname" value="SMITH CARR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2985" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2985" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18290409-322-viclabel1818" type="occupation">shopkeer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-victim2982 t18290409-322-viclabel1818"></join>, and live at No. 90, <placeName id="t18290409-322-crimeloc1819">Charles-street, Hatton-garden, in the parish of St. Andrew, Holborn</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-crimeloc1819" type="placeName" value="Charles-street, Hatton-garden, in the parish of St. Andrew, Holborn"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-crimeloc1819" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-off1814 t18290409-322-crimeloc1819"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-322-off1817 t18290409-322-crimeloc1819"></join>. I occupy the two shops and two attics, in which I have two persons put in to take care of the house; it is a corner house - I let the house to different lodgers; I let one kitchen to a Mr. Ewer, the other kitchen I keep for the accommodation of the lodgers - the cellar may be about ten yards from the kitchen-door - I leave my shop every night for my residence at Holloway; I left it on Tuesday evening, the 17th of March, as near half-past nine o'clock as I can recollect - before I left it, I took down my cash-box into my cellar, in which was enclosed three 20l. notes, I can swear, but I believe there were four, upwards of 50 sovereigns, from 5l. to 7l. in silver, and amongst the silver was a bad crown-piece, with a piece cut out of the edge of it nearly the eighth of an inch, and two bills of exchange - I locked my cash-box, put it into an iron chest in the cellar; I locked the chest and the cellar-door - my shop was shutting up at this time; I waited till I saw the shop-doors closed, and then set off for Holloway - the next morning I received some information, a little after nine o'clock, and went down into the cellar with a light; I found the cellar-door broken open, and the iron chest gone, and a chisel was lying on the ledge where the iron-chest had been placed - the chisel is in the possession of the constable; I should know it again- I found my iron-chest the same morning at the house of a chimney-sweeper, named Brown, in Feather's-court, Fox-court - I have no doubt it was my chest; the prisoner Hawkins came to live with me, I think in December, 1826, and left me last September; he must have seen me going down stairs to deposit my cash-box in the cellar, as as it has been my custom for the last six months - the kitchen is at the corner of Charles-street.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. You sleep at Holloway? A. Yes. Mr. Ewer, Miss Wellyer and some other persons lodge at my house in Charles-street, some of them had servants; one of their servants is here- I always sleep at Holloway; it is there my family reside.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2986">
                  JAMES 
                  OWEN
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2986" type="surname" value="OWEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2986" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2986" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. Ewer. He lodges at Mr. Carr's; on the night of the 17th of March, I left the kitchen window shut down but not fastened, and one shutter shut - I cannot tell what time of night it was; I have been there a year and a quarter - and that was the usual mode of leaving the window and shutter; I went down the next morning, and saw the kitchen door open which had been fastened with a padlock; the padlock was hanging by the hasp, but the hasp had been forced out- the window sash was up, and the shutters both back; this was about nine o'clock - I did not observe the cellar door then, but I did afterwards, and saw a piece had been broken out of it; I did not go into the cellar.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. How many servants were in the house altogether at that time? A. Four- some men and some women; I left the house at nine o'clock at night; I cannot say that I left the other servants all up - I suppose they would not be gone to bed; they are not here; I do not know whether they were up or not.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2987">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  BOWERS
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2987" type="surname" value="BOWERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2987" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2987" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pot boy to Mr. Bowers, who keeps the Pewter Platter public-house, in Charles-<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090151"></xptr>street - I am his nephew. On the night of the 17th of March I was in Charles-street about half-past nine o'clock, near the house of Mr. Carr - I saw a person near his house, it was a young man - I was two or three yards from him, and I stopped and looked at him; he called me several had words, and said, if I did not go on he would kick my little guts out - that was 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2988">
                  John 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2988" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2988" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2988" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; I went on, and stood in the middle of the street, and saw a young man come out of Mr.Carr's area;
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2989">
                  John 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2989" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2989" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2989" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was at that time standing against the gateway; they crossed the road together - I have no doubt about John Ballard being the person - I had known him by sight before, and observed him particularly.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did you observe the dress of the other man? A. Yes - he had a dark blue coat and trousers.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. How old are you? A. Eleven years: I have never been in a church or a chapel in my life; I have never been taught my prayers; I know what the meaning of an oath is - if I tell a lie I shall go to hell; no one told me to say that - I have heard it from several people just before I went to the office - it was not told me by any of the officers - it was told me by a gentleman, who was a stranger to me -I did not ask him what business he had to tell me that- I have never seen him since, and had no conversation with him but that; he came into our house about seven o'clock in the morning, while I was clearing up the place - it was the day I was coming up to Hatton-garden - he asked me, whether I knew the nature of an oath? -I told him no, I did not: he said, if you tell a lie, you will go to hell; he stopped in the tap-room - he did not say, if the magistrate asked me, I was to give him that answer - the gentleman had never spoken to me in my life before - I should not know him again; no one ever told me the nature of an oath but that gentleman; I have a father living, he never told me so.</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH. Q. Your uncle keeps a public-house, and has a good deal to do? A. yes; we work on Sundays as as well as other days.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Was that the first day you ever heard hell mentioned? A. No; I suppose bell to be a wicked place - that person told me if I told lies I should go to that wicked place - I believe that now; I have heard about religion before that - I do not know the Commandments -I do not know my duty to God - I have lived in that public-house three years; I have known Hawkins, as living in the service of Mr. Carr - if the other young man had been Hawkins I should have known him; but I am sure it was not; when they crossed the road they went towards Brooke-street.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2990">
                  SAMUEL 
                  SANDELL
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2990" type="surname" value="SANDELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2990" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2990" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a hair-dresser. and live at No.1, Dorrington-street, Brook's-market - I occupy the shop and parlour; there is a yard just large enough for the water-hutt, and there is a tenement there, consisting of two rooms, which is occupied by 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2991">
                  George 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2991" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2991" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2991" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and his wife; they have three sons, who live with them - a passage leads into their apartment; I have a door leading from my back parlour into the passage. On Tuesday night, the 17th of March, a little after ten o'clock, it might be a quarter past, I heard something fall down in the passage very heavy - it gave an alarm; I took the candle, and went out - I saw two persons; John Ballard was one - I have no doubt of him; he was sitting on a chest, and the other was standing on the step of the door with his back towards me; I said, "What is all this noise about?" Ballard told me to call his mother, and said he wanted no light - the noise I heard shook the partition: I asked Ballard who his mother was, and he said Ballard - I opened the back door, called Mrs. Ballard, and then I went into my room; the next morning I opened my door to get some water, and Mrs. Ballard said to me, "Come up stairs, and I will shew you the box that was let down last night" - she said it was let down by her son; I went up stairs, and saw a wooden box with some mouldings in it for cielings, such as plasterers use - I did not go near enough to see whether the mouldings were broken, or not; I cannot say whether it was the box which I had seen the night before - I did not examine it at all.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. You would not know what sort of a noise it would make? A. No; it is not a private passage - there are a good many persons come into it: I knew John Ballard before, but I did not know him that night till he spoke, and ordered me to call his mother; I believe they have three sons and one daughter, but 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2992">
                  John 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2992" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2992" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2992" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             has a more manly voice than the others - the eldest of the others is about fourteen; I do not swear to him by his voice - I am not very found of dogs, but I have had a good deal to do with them.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BONKIN. Q. There was another person? A. Yes, on the stop of the door - his back was towards me; my candle was lighted, and I went out directly after I heard the noise - I had not heard any person call a man at the door to help him.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. You do not know that it was Ballard, except by his calling his mother? A. No - I saw his face then; I did not know him till he spoke; I have seen him before going up and down - I did not see his face; he held his head down - I took no notice that night of the face or person of the other man; his mother came down directly.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2993">
                  ANDREW 
                  DOWDEN
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2993" type="surname" value="DOWDEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2993" type="given" value="ANDREW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2993" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a cabinet-maker. On the night of Tuesday, the 17th of March, I was with the last witness, about ten o'clock; I heard a great noise in the passage - it seemed as if all the partition was coming down; what it was I cannot tell - I went into the passage along with Sandell; I saw two young men - one was sitting on the box, and the other standing on the step of the door; I was not near the box- I was behind Mr. Sandell: I was not near enough to see what sort of a box it was - the one on the box said to Mr.Sandell, with an oath, "Go in, for I want no light here;" he asked him to call his mother, and Sandell asked him what his mother's name was - he said Mrs. Ballard; Sandell called her and when she came down she asked him for a light; he did not give her one, as the young man said he wanted no light there; I did not notice who they were.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2994">
                  JAMES 
                  OSHORNE
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2994" type="surname" value="OSHORNE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2994" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2994" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My father is a coach-wheelwright; we live in Dorrington-street, Brookes-market - I was twelve years old on the 24th of March; I go to church-I know the Lord's Prayer; I do not know what the nature of an oath is; I know I must always speak the truth, if I do not, I shall go to hell.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. What do you call the Lord's Prayer? how does it begin? A."Our Father, which art in Heaven," &amp;c.</p>

               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090152"></xptr>MR. SMITH. Q. Do you remember, on the evening of the 17th of March, going on an errand? A. Yes, my mother sent me about half-past ten o'clock at night: I had to pass through the passage of the house we live in; there is a partition between Mr. Sandell's parlour and the passage - I saw a chest in the passage, and John Ballard standing by it; I know him-that is him; I have no doubt about it - I am sure it was him; there was another person standing on the step of the door - that person was George Hawkins;that is him: I sawMrs.Ballardcome down - 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2995">
                  John 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2995" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2995" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2995" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             told her she was always a-bed; she had no light-she asked for one from Mr. Sandell; John Ballard said, "We want no light here" - I saw John Ballard and Hawkings take hold of each end of the chest and take it up stairs; it appeared to me to be a heavy chest: before I came down, while I was up stairs, I heard something fall very heavy in the passage - I went on my errand, and returned in about five minutes; when I re turned I heard a very heavy knocking in Ballard's room- I was in my own room, which is about three feet from Ballard's house; the noise appeared to be like something very hard - like something knocking against iron;Ihave been near a blacksmith's shop, and heard the noise directly I came back; I went to bed when the noise had ceased,</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Were you examined at the Police Office? A. Yes; I stated there that Mr. Sandell came to the passage, and the light was asked for.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by Mr. BODKIN. Q. Do you live in small house? A. No, they live in a small house in the yard; I knew Ballards before -I had never seen Hawkins before; Mr.Sandell staid with the light till they were up stairs - that was two or three minutes, or more than that; it might be five minutes he said at his own parlour door in the passage; and there is a passage, and then there is another passage goes down; and his door is in that - Hawkins was at the step of the door at the end of the passage next the street, a good way from the candle.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. How could you see him so well? A. I saw him when he came along the passage with the chest- when I came back they were up stairs.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2996">
                  ANN 
                  OSBORNE
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2996" type="surname" value="OSBORNE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2996" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2996" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the mother of this witness. On Tuesday night, the 17th of March, I sent him out on an errand; I heard a very heavy fall in the passage before he went down, and I kept him a minute or two till I heard the sound of voices, and then I sent him down; this was a little after ten o'clock - after he came back I asked him what that swearing was, which I heard in the passage, and in a few minutes I heard something like a very heavy breaking; I cannot exactly describe it - it was very heavy,like knocking against something very hard, very loud, and it shook my room; it continned about twenty minutes, more or less, and appeared to come from the back house, which is out in the yard, and which is occupied by the Ballards - there was no other house from which it could come.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2997">
                  MARY 
                  DENTRY
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2997" type="surname" value="DENTRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2997" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2997" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a grand-daughter of Mr. Sandell, and live there. On the night of the 17th of March I saw two men about twenty minutes after eleven o'clock, just at the corner of Dorrington-street; I do not know who they were - they were going from the yard, up towards Brook-street; one of them had something on his shoulder, which appeared very heavy by the way he carried it: When I saw them they were near our door,about six feet from the passage.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. You cannot tell whether they had been in the yard? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person2998">
                  JAMES 
                  HANKS
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2998" type="surname" value="HANKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2998" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2998" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a carver and gilder, and live at No. I, Dorrington-street, Brook's-market. On Wednesday, the 18th of March, about seven o'clock in the evening, I was at the street door in company with Culmore, and heard the cry of Murder! which seemed to come from the back premises occupied by Ballards; I know old Ballard and his wife well - Culmore and I went to the back premises, and when we got into the yard I heard the voice of Mrs. Ballard, which proceeded from Ballard's apartments; she said 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person2999">
                  Joseph 
                  Ince
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2999" type="surname" value="Ince"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2999" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person2999" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             should not have the money; I heard a kind of scuffle and other voices in the room - I heard Joseph Ince say if any person was mistrustful of his having the money he would give it up to any one they chuse; we then heard three or four voices say, "Let old Ballard have it;" we then heard the counting of money, which appeared as if counted on a table or a board; and it appeared, by the sound, to be sovereigns - we heard luch count one, two three,till he came to twenty-one sovereigns; and then there were two half-sovereigns, which he said made 22l. - we then heard a young woman's voice say she did not expect her brother John to wear two faces under one hat that morning; when the voices said Mr.Ballard should have it, Ballard said he would take care of it, it should not see either sun or moon.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Are you sure it was old Ballard's voice said that? A. Yes, it was then nearly eight o'clock,</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR.PHILLIPS. Q. These people must have taken uncommon pains for you to hear them; did they talk very loud? A. They did talk loudish; the upper door was closed - I know the sound of sovereigns from shillings if they chinked, that I will swear; I was at the bottom of the stairs; there are ten stairs - I was about three yards from them; I have always gone by the name of 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person3000">
                  James 
                  Hanks
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3000" type="surname" value="Hanks"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3000" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3000" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , unless they call me Jem; Hanks is the surname I have always gone by, never by any other; I was never here before, nor in the other Court - there was a charge made against me at Hatton-garden, by Mr. Dupree, of No. 10,Dorrington-street. a composition maker, for taking a sixpence and 3d. in halfpence; I am sure there was never any other charge made against me; there was no charge about jewellery;I was tried at Hicks-hall upon Mr. Dupree's charge, and acquitted - it is seven years ago; I am now nineteen years of age; Mr. Dupree was my master then - I live up stairs in the front house at No. 1, Dorrington-street; there might be twelve or fourteen people living in the front house or more; the back house is not more than four feet from the front house - I cannot say whether the people in the front house could hear this; they might be out.</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH. Q. Have you any doubt of your being correct in what you have stated? A. What I have stated I did hear.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3001">
                  CHARLES 
                  CULMORE
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3001" type="surname" value="CULMORE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3001" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3001" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a cutler, and live in Beanchamp street. I was in company with Hanks on Wednesday night,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090153"></xptr>the 18th of March, about half-past six or nearer seven o'clock - we were standing at the street door, No.1, Dorrington-street, and I heard Murder called; we went into the back yard near the premises,occupied by the Ballards only - I heard Mrs. Ballard's voice, she was beating 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person3002">
                  Ivy 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3002" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3002" type="given" value="Ivy"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3002" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and somebody said, "Don't kick him, Mrs. Ballard; and I heard Ballard's sister say,"Oh, my poor brother! I did not think he carried two faces under one hat this morning;" I then heard Mrs.Ballard say she would have the money. she wanted the money - and two or three voices said,"The old man shall have it."</p>
               <p>Cross-exmined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Was it before the money was counted that the sister said she did not think her brother carried two faces under one hat? A. Yes; I was standing at the yard door - lvy then came down with a light, as he had some suspicion of somebody overhearing them; Hanks went into the passage to avoid being seen, and I went into the water-closet; and said in a good loud voice, "Who is there?" I said, "Me;" he said who was me - and I did not answer him; Hanks was somewhere about the passage - I do not know whether he was near enough to hear Ivy call; Ivy looked about, and opened the yard door, but could not see Hanks - he looked about the yard and the dust-hole, and then went up stairs; I believe Hanks did not come back into the yard.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. You heard nothing but conversation? A. No; I did not hear the money counted out, nor any thing about that, because I was further off than Hanks was - I was by the yard door,holding it open in case any body should come with a light.</p>
               <p>Q. What do you mean by saying you did not hear the money counted out? A. Because Hanks heard it - he said so to me.</p>
               <p>Q. You told the Magistrate they counted money - how came you to state that, if you did not hear it? A. Because old Ballard said it should not see sun nor moon; and so I thought that he did have money.</p>
               <p>Q. Was that your reason for supposing he did have money, and for saying they counted it? A. Yes, I have got a slight memory - I did not recollect it.</p>
