                  </persName>
             there in the afternoon; I knew them perfectly-these are the persons; when I went in, Ballard was playing at bagatelle - there was young man there whom I knew, named Williams; Ballard lost two pots of ale - he paid the landlord for three pints, and said he would pay the other next day; the landlord said he ought not to play without he had money - he then went away; Hawkins then played for half a pound of beaf steaks, and lost - he went out to fetch them, but did not return; I went home to tea about five o'clock, and re turned about seven - Hawkins came in and sat down by the side of Hawkins - they spoke to each other, but I did not hear what they said; Ballard rose up, pulled a chisel out of his breast, and showed it to Hawkins - Hawkins turned round side ways, and said, "It is just the thing;" my attention was drawn to it; I thought there was something going on wrong, and I observed it particularly, so that if I saw it again I should know it - I have seen it since in the possession of the beadle; I did not take hold of it till I was at Hatton-garden - I was sure it was the same that I had seen: they said about an hour longer at the public-house, and then went away together - this was about a quarter past eight, I believe, but the clock did not go right; they returned about a quarter past ten, and called out a young man named Riley, who had been asleep there for four or five hours they touched him, and he followed them out; they paid something - I remained there till a quarter before twelve; I am quite sure this is the chisel- it is made out of an old file.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR.PHILLIPS. Q. This chisel they were showing openly? A. No.; I had an opportunity of seeing it for about a couple of seconds - I knew it instantly when I saw it the next day; there were some of Ballard's relations in the public-house, playing at bagatelle, and one young man that beat him out of the steaks- I have been here before for my own property; I was tried for a game cock, as they called,it, but I was honourably acquitted - I was not up above a minute and a half, and you were my counsel; there were one or two witnesses examined, but it did not last above a minute and a half - I never heard of any body saying they could swear a spot off a tea-kettle; I never said that unless I got a pound, I would swear a spout off a tea-kettle - I never said, in the presence of Badland and another person, that I knew nothing about this robbery; they offered me 10l., but I did not see why I should not be in it as well as other people; they tried to buy me to keep out of the way - I was never accused of any thing beside the game cock, unless it was fighting now and then; there never was a young woman who lost any clothes, and brought a charge against me - it was in October Session I was tried about the game cuck; I know Badland perfectly well - he is the landlord of that public-house, and I know 
