                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3010" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep the Blackamoor's Head in Brookes-market; I have kept it about three months, On Tuesday afternoon. the 17th March, I recollect seeing Hawkins and Ballard the younger in my house; I know<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090154"></xptr>them - these are them; there were several other persons there - in consequence of their having played a games, Ballard came and paid me for one pint of ale, and left one pint unpaid; they were in and out, in the course of the afternoon - they went out, and returned about eight o'clock, and were there from ten till half-past ten; on their return Hawkins asked me what he owed me - I told him, and he paid me 4s. 9d. or 4s.9 1/2d., with five shillings in silver, and I saw from seven to ten shillings in his hand; I saw Lewis there in the afternoon, and in the evening also - he was three from three to four hours altogether.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR.BODKIN. Q. Did you know of any gambling going forward in your house? A. Yes, bagatelle; I did not state before the Magistrate there was no gambling: in my house that night - I said ther were no cards; I will swear I told the Magistrate I did not see any gambling: I am not in the habit of frequenting that room- I was told of it by my servant, the day following; I never said" You should not have paid for what you can't pay for," to the best of my knowledge: I did not know there had been any gambling till the next day - I do not believe I said that.</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH. Q. When he came to the bar, and paid you for one pint, and left one pint unpaid, what did you say? A. I said I was not in the habit of giving credit, and I would not, and he said he would return and pay me.</p>
