                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3023" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ) - I have had conversation with him many times; I never said there was a jemmy produced, and that I knew more about the transaction than any one else - he never said to me,"You made this jemmy," nor did I answer I did - I have knwon him before; he is a particular friend of mine.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR.BODKIN. Q. You said you saw the chisel for two seconds? A. Yes; Ballard shewed it to Hawkins, and Hawkins laid hold of it in his hand; I do not think I said that before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3024">
                  JOHN 
                  BARNLEY
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3024" type="surname" value="BARNLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3024" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3024" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. Q. Have you tried this chisel any where? A. Yes, to the kitchen door at Mr. Carr's, and it exactly fitted the wrench in the door where the lock was forced: I also tried it to the inner cellar door, and it corresponded there.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you say that at Hatton - garden? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3025">
                  ANDREW 
                  LLOYD
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3025" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3025" type="given" value="ANDREW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3025" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of Hatton-garden. I produce an iron chest which I got from a man of the name of Brown, in Feathers-court, Fox-court - I have had it ever since; I searched Ballard's house, but found nothing; I saw a deal box there, which contained what I believe they call enrichments - it was not broken at all they were plaster of Paris chimney ornaments - if that box had been let fall. they would have been broken - if I had let one of them fall it would have been broken.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Have you broght it here? A. No, it was not very heavy; I searched the the house accurately on the 18th, and found on 20l. Bank notes or bills - it was about one o'clock in the day -Barnley and I were together.</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH. Q. Bills of exchange and notes are more traceable than gold and silver, are they not? A. Yes; I have a blue coat here, which Ballard's mother told me I had just been taken off that morning.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. You cannot tell how long it had been taken off? A. No, I was at the office when that coat was shown to Bowers.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3026">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  BOWERS
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3026" type="surname" value="BOWERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3026" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . That is not the coat one of the men had on, the night in question.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. How do you know? A. It looked a newer one - it had shiny buttons.</p>
               <p>MR. CARR. This is my chest.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3027">
                  JOSEPH 
                  MARRIAGE
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3027" type="surname" value="MARRIAGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3027" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This is the chest I saw, and I dragged it into the yard.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3028">
                  JAMES 
                  OSBORNE
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3028" type="surname" value="OSBORNE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3028" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3028" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . That is like the chest I saw carried out - I could not tell whether it was wood or iron.</p>
               <p>HAWKIN's Defence. I solemnly declare my innocence of the crime, and I hope the Jury will take all the statements into consideration in my behalf.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3029">
                  JOHN 
                  BALLARD
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3029" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3029" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3029" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's Defence. I have witnesses to prove that I was not in Charles-street that night; and that I was not in the public-house at the time Lewis swears I gave the chisel out of my hosom; he said it was about nine o'clock, and now he says after ten.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3030">
                  GEORGE 
                  BALLARD
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3030" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3030" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3030" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's Defence. I never saw that chest, nor any thing belonging to it in my life; I never had such property as that young man swears to, for these sixteen years, except it was my employer's.</p>
               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-defend3032" type="defendantName">
                     ANN 
                     BALLARD
                  <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend3032" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend3032" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-defend3032" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            's Defence. Hanks says he will swear to my voice, but he never knew me till within five weeks; we had not given up housekeeping more than five weeks before this happened: I will be on my solemn oath that he never saw me on that night, or heard me, except going out for my supper beer, or so. I hope you will not suffer, the evidence of such a boy as that to convict me; the first at Hatton-garden, and I was not afraid of going; he knows his mother went down on her knees to the gentleman, and he being a humane gentleman, would not take advantage of her son.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3033">
                  JOHN 
                  GRIFFITHS
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3033" type="surname" value="GRIFFITHS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3033" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3033" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a draper. I have no knowledge of the prisoners; I believe I never spoke to them in my life: Lewis had been giving evidence, and he told me a jemmy had been produced at the office; I asked if he knew where it came from; he said he knew all about it; I asked if he knew where it came from; he said he did; I said, "I suppose you made it?" Yes (said he) I did."</p>
               <p>MR. SMITH. Q. Who do you live with? A. I am out of a situation; the last situation I had was with 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person3034">
                  John 
                  Edward Smee
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3034" type="surname" value="Edward Smee"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3034" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3034" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , Crown-court, Cheapside - I left on the 1st of March, and I have not been employed since then; I have been occasionally at the Blackamoor's Head, not very often, perhaps twice or three times a week; I would not swear I have not been there four or five times, I should not think I have been more than three times - I have played at bagatelle there perhaps half a dozen times; between the 1st and 17th of March I do not think I played more than three or four times; I have played at cards perhaps three or four times, at whist; that is the only game I recollect - I do not know the game of put, therefore I do not think that I ever played at it - I do not recollect playing at put, or any game except whist; I have made one at a game of put, but I do not know the game; I have not played at put in that house, to my recollection, and I will swear I did not play with any of the prisoners at the bar - I may have played at put, but not with one of them; I will swear I have not played any game with any of them: I have seen Hawkins there, perhaps, half a dozen times, but I do not recollect having ever changed a word with either of them - I went to Hatton-garden with Mr. Badland; I know him perfectly well- I have been an inmate of his house for the last three weeks; I went from curiosity more than any thing else, as I had heard of the robbery - I know Lewis by sight, nothing more; I was not inquisitive about this chisel, but he put a number of questions to me; he came first and sat down very near me, at Mr. Badland's, and commenced the conversation; there was several persons present, but I do not recollect any one that I knew - it did not occur to me to make any inquiries, or to communicate this conversation; it was no business of mine - it was on the day of the second or third examination.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090156"></xptr>MR. PHILLIPS. Q. How came you to leave the drapers? A. They failed and were in the Gazette; I had been with them about two months. I am single.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. What did Lewis say? A. He turned towards me, and said there was a jemmy produced at the office; that was what began it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3035">
                  HANNAH 
                  CROWDER
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3035" type="surname" value="CROWDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3035" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3035" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I know John Ballard; his mother is my husband's sister. On the evening of the 17th of March I saw him at my house, I think about nine o'clock; he staid, I suppose, nearly three quarters of an hour, and left near ten - I live at No. 17, Bell-court, Gray's Inn-lane; he worked for me some years - he had home a good character; I have intrusted him to pay and receive many pounds, and never had a furthing mistake with him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-322-person3036">
                  CHARLES 
                  RINGER
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3036" type="surname" value="RINGER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3036" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3036" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a locksmith, and live in Bellcourt. I have known 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person3037">
                  John 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3037" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3037" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3037" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             eighteen years. I never heard any thing against his character in my life; he has always been a good young man.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. SMITH. Q. You know the other Ballards? A. Yes, by sight; I have not met the woman any where within the last six weeks; I have never since the robbery said that either that woman or her daughter had the sovereigns about her; I have never said that either the mother or the daughter had the sovereigns concealed in their hair; I never said that to</p>
               <p>Mr. Carr.</p>
               <p>MR. CARR re-examined. Q. Does the cellar open into the kitchen? A. No, into the passage, about ten yards, from the kitchen door; there is no opening from the cellar to the street - you go into the cellor without going into the air.</p>
               <p>MR. BODKIN. Q. Were the servants that were in the house belonging to yourself? A. They are not servants of mine - they were put in by myself to take care of the house; I give them the place to sleep in - I never sleep there my self-they are not servants of mine,neither of them.</p>

               <p>Three witnesses gave Hawkins a good character, one deposed the same for John Ballard, and four for 
               <persName id="t18290409-322-person3038">
                  George 
                  Ballard
               <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3038" type="surname" value="Ballard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3038" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-322-person3038" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>

